nts aim to combine academic and business skills to establish a better understanding of the extent to which games-based learning has the potential to support the problem-based learning and soft skills increasingly required in tertiary education and the workplace. The project will examine the integration of a variety of group problem solving games developed by TPLD into first and third year social science modules. These modules have been explicitly redesigned to have a strong focus on skills. Consideration will be given to how the games meet the learning outcomes of the modules and how difficulties which arise for students when working in groups can be tackled. Students' perceptions of the game and its relevance to the acquisition of group skills will be evaluated.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The business/academic collaboration will also examine the extent to which team games can be developed to help players to make better decisions in the domain of social problem solving and decision making in social science. The aim here is not to develop a game but to gain a better understanding and develop a clearer specification of what kinds of problem solving games might be suitable for future implementation in the social sciences.
